\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: QR and orthogonal bases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=QR$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=RQ$
\end_inset

 have the same eigenvalues, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a square matrix.
 Then do a little experiment: Construct a random 
\begin_inset Formula $10\times10$
\end_inset

 real-symmetric matrix in Matlab via 
\family typewriter
X=rand(10,10); A = X' * X
\family default
.
 Use 
\family typewriter
[Q,R] = qr(A)
\family default
 to compute the QR factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and then compute 
\begin_inset Formula $B=RQ$
\end_inset

.
 Then find the QR factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $B=Q'R'$
\end_inset

, and compute 
\begin_inset Formula $R'Q'$
\end_inset

...repeat this process until the matrix converges.
 From what it converges to, suggest a procedure to compute the eigenvalues
 and eigenvectors of a matrix (no need to prove that it converges in general).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The book suggests this procedure to solve least-square problems 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}Ax=A^{*}b$
\end_inset

: instead of computing 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\hat{Q}\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 and then solving 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}x=\hat{Q}^{*}b$
\end_inset

, you should instead form the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $B=(A,b)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 columns, do QR factorization to get 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\hat{Q}'\hat{R}'$
\end_inset

 and then solve 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}'_{1:n,1:n}x=\hat{R}'_{1:n,n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, it claims that the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}'$
\end_inset

 give 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

, and that the last column of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}'$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{Q}^{*}b$
\end_inset

.
 Explain why this must be true, regardless of what QR algorithm is used
 (don't use the specific structure of the Householder algorithm as the book
 does, use the definition of the QR factorization).
\end_layout

